    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1951-01-18T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1951-01-18T12:00:00-05:00" n="74"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d74">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">795.00/1–1851: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gifford</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                        <lb/>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">
                            <gloss target="#t_niact1">niact</gloss>
                        </hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1951-01-18T17:00:00+00:00"
                            >January 18, 1951—5 p. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>3985. <gloss target="#t_Embtel1">Embtel</gloss> 3975, January 18;<note n="1"
                        xml:id="d74fn1">Not printed. It reported British reaction that the response
                        of the Chinese Communists to the cease-fire proposals was “most
                        discouraging”, but went on to say that there was general agreement in
                        British Government circles that the United Nations should not be rushed into
                        further action without time for thorough consideration of the consequences.
                        (795.00/1–1851)</note> repeated <gloss target="#t_USUN2">USUN</gloss>
                    69.</p>
                <p>Foreign Office has just telegraphed instructions to <gloss target="#t_UKUN1"
                        >UKUN</gloss> stating UK finds terms Chinese reply to cease-fire resolution
                    unacceptable and authorizing Jebb “have good smack at it”. <gloss
                        target="#t_UKUN1">UKUN</gloss> informed UK <pb facs="0117" n="101"
                        xml:id="pg_101"/> hopes US will not insist on introducing new resolution
                    today. If US does insist, and resolution introduced by <gloss target="#t_USUN2"
                        >USUN</gloss> is along lines described London [<hi rend="italic"
                        >Department</hi>] circular 387,<note n="2" xml:id="d74fn2">Dated January 15,
                            <ref target="#pg_83">p. 83</ref>.</note> UK would wish have it amended.
                    UK would prefer have condemnatory resolution handled separately from any
                    resolution calling for further UN action and not combined in one document.</p>
                <p>Sent Department 3985, repeated info <hi rend="smallcaps">
                        <gloss target="#t_niact1">niact</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <gloss target="#t_USUN2">USUN</gloss> 61.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gifford</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
